of the thing you measured.

1442
00:49:45,920 --> 00:49:46,520
So,

1443
00:49:46,520 --> 00:49:49,620
it may have started in an eigenstate of angular momentum,

1444
00:49:50,260 --> 00:49:51,560
you measure it,

1445
00:49:51,560 --> 00:49:53,740
and all of a sudden it's in a state

1446
00:49:53,740 --> 00:49:55,140
of definite orientation.

1447
00:49:57,180 --> 00:49:58,980
Is a state of definite orientation,

1448
00:49:59,420 --> 00:50:00,920
does it have a definite angular momentum?

1449
00:50:04,160 --> 00:50:06,120
The analogous question would be,

1450
00:50:06,220 --> 00:50:08,900
for a particle which has a definite position,

1451
00:50:09,500 --> 00:50:11,160
does it have a definite momentum?

1452
00:50:12,440 --> 00:50:13,400
The answer is,

1453
00:50:13,400 --> 00:50:13,640
of course,

1454
00:50:13,640 --> 00:50:13,780
no.

1455
00:50:13,940 --> 00:50:15,060
That's the uncertainty principle.

1456
00:50:15,760 --> 00:50:19,020
And the same is true with angular momentum and angle.

1457
00:50:19,800 --> 00:50:21,280
If you measure the thing and

1458
00:50:21,280 --> 00:50:22,760
you kick it into a state

1459
00:50:22,760 --> 00:50:23,760
of a definite orientation,

1460
00:50:24,540 --> 00:50:25,560
you must have a definite angular momentum.

1461
00:50:25,580 --> 00:50:30,860
You must have given a kick to its angular momentum.

1462
00:50:31,340 --> 00:50:33,180
Same kind of Heisenberg story.

1463
00:50:33,420 --> 00:50:34,400
If you measure the position,

1464
00:50:34,400 --> 00:50:36,380
you give it a knock

1465
00:50:36,380 --> 00:50:37,980
and you influence its momentum.

1466
00:50:38,480 --> 00:50:42,480
If you measure the orientation of the molecule,

1467
00:50:42,780 --> 00:50:44,660
you affect its angular momentum.

1468
00:50:45,339 --> 00:50:49,260
But what if the spectrum of energy levels is such

1469
00:50:49,260 --> 00:50:52,640
that the first angular momentum excitation

1470
00:50:52,640 --> 00:50:55,420
is just more energy than you have available

1471
00:50:55,580 --> 00:51:00,320
in your photons that are doing the measuring?

1472
00:51:01,450 --> 00:51:06,220
What if the energy to the first excited rotational state

1473
00:51:06,220 --> 00:51:08,060
is gigantic for some reason?

1474
00:51:09,300 --> 00:51:15,860
Then your apparatus simply cannot resolve the orientation.

1475
00:51:16,800 --> 00:51:18,540
So it becomes a question,

1476
00:51:18,540 --> 00:51:19,900
given your apparatus,

1477
00:51:20,280 --> 00:51:22,480
what is the excitable?

1478
00:51:22,480 --> 00:51:24,000
How much energy does it take

1479
00:51:24,000 --> 00:51:27,860
to excite the first angular momentum state?

1480
00:51:28,400 --> 00:51:28,940
Now,

1481
00:51:28,940 --> 00:51:30,500
for a basketball or a dumbbell,

1482
00:51:30,920 --> 00:51:32,060
a real dumbbell,

1483
00:51:32,360 --> 00:51:35,220
the energy separation between the first state

1484
00:51:35,220 --> 00:51:37,160
and the second state is incredibly small.

1485
00:51:37,340 --> 00:51:38,540
You can figure it out yourself.

1486
00:51:38,800 --> 00:51:39,700
There's moment of inertia.

1487
00:51:40,040 --> 00:51:42,080
There's quantization of angular momentum.

1488
00:51:42,280 --> 00:51:43,020
You can figure it out.

1489
00:51:43,620 --> 00:51:48,120
But the separation of energy levels is incredibly small.

1490
00:51:48,820 --> 00:51:52,140
So it's not surprising that with an ordinary light,

1491
00:51:52,140 --> 00:51:55,540
you can measure the orientation of the dumbbell.

1492
00:51:56,820 --> 00:52:00,200
It doesn't take very much energy

1493
00:52:00,200 --> 00:52:04,640
to kick the dumbbell into a state of definite orientation.

1494
00:52:05,560 --> 00:52:06,920
But for a molecule,

1495
00:52:07,200 --> 00:52:10,140
the energy levels are somewhat spread.

